Dawn in the city of Tel-Sarrow was a grey smear, the sun struggling to pierce the perpetual haze of smoke from the tanneries and smithies. After three days of hard travel, the pastoral silence was now a distant memory, replaced by the low, constant rumble of a city stirring to life. Kael waited by the East Gate, his few possessions—a bedroll, a waterskin, and the weight of his purpose—strapped securely to his back, as he scanned the faces of the merchants and guards for the one he had been told to meet. The air here tasted of coal dust and offal, a far cry from the dew-soaked fields he had left behind, but it was here his new life would begin, or end.a waterskin, and the long, cloth-wrapped bundle—strapped securely to his back. The bundle seemed to thrum with a familiar, dormant energy, a counterpoint to the weary ache in his limbs from a night without rest. Around him, the city stirred to life: cart wheels clattering on cobbles, the distant clang of a forge, the murmur of early merchants. He kept his hood drawn up, not against the damp chill alone, but against recognition. The gate guards paid him little mind, just another itinerant soul drawn to the road at first light. He focused on the archway of weathered stone, seeing not the gate but the path beyond, a ribbon of dirt leading away from the smoke and memory, into the uncertain grey of the new day.a waterskin, a whetstone he never used—in a pack on his back. Oathkeeper was a familiar, guilty weight on his hip. He’d used a few coppers of Anya’s advance to buy a waxed cloak and some hardtack. The rest sat in his purse, a guilty, glorious anchor.

Sister Anya arrived as the portcullis was being winched up. She moved with a quiet efficiency, her robes exchanged for tougher, travel-worn versions of the same, her satchel still across her chest. She carried a simple staff of dark wood. She nodded to him, no smile, and they passed under the iron teeth of the gate without a word.

The road quickly deteriorated from packed earth to a rutted track, the city’s stench giving way to the dry, alkaline smell of the approaching Wastes. They walked in silence for an hour, the only sounds their footsteps and the distant caw of carrion birds. Kael’s senses, dulled by years of drink and regret, began to prickle awake. He scanned the scrubland automatically, noting the lay of the land, the places for ambush, the best paths for quick retreat. It was a muscle memory, painful in its resurgence.

“You don’t ask why I chose you,” Anya said suddenly, her voice cutting the silence.

“The coin chose me,” Kael replied.

“It’s more than that. At Greywall… you were the only one who came out alive from the inner keep. The only one who saw what happened.”

Ice water flooded Kael’s veins. He stopped walking. “What do you know of Greywall?”

She turned to face him, her slate eyes grave. “I know it fell in a single night when it should have held for a month. I know the Sorcerer-King’s forces were said to have used dark magic to breach walls that had never fallen. I know you were the last commander standing.” She paused. “And I know an oath was broken there. Not just yours. Many.”

“You know nothing,” he snarled, the words tearing from a raw place. “You read it in a book. You didn’t smell the blood. You didn’t hear the…” He choked off, seeing the faces again. Not the enemy’s. His own men’s. As the silence spread from the inner keep, as they realized no orders were coming.

“I am not your judge, Kael,” Anya said softly. “I am a seeker of truths. Sometimes they are buried in ruins. Sometimes they are carried by broken men.”

“What truth are you seeking in a dusty chapel?” he asked, his anger subsiding into a weary suspicion.

“A confirmation,” she said, and would elaborate no further. She resumed walking.

Frustrated, Kael fell in beside her, his hand resting once more on the rusted hilt. The past was a clawed thing in his chest, and she had just raked it open. He wanted to turn back, to return her silver and lose himself in the city’s filth. But the coin felt like a chain now, pulling him forward.

As they reached the final rise before the land truly broke into the cracked badlands of the Ashen Wastes, Kael glanced back one last time at the distant, hazy silhouette of Tel-Sarrow. His eyes dropped to the massive, weathered gatepost they had passed just an hour before.

And there it was.

Carved into the grey stone, fresh enough that the chisel marks showed pale against the weathered surface, was a sigil. A single, stylized eye, with a serpent coiled where the pupil should be. It was no crude graffiti. It was precise, deliberate.

The Eye of Tel. The mark of the Sorcerer-King.

Kael’s breath froze in his lungs. It was a watching mark. A ward, or a warning. Placed here, on the road to the Wastes. Coincidence was a luxury men like him couldn’t afford.

He looked sharply at Anya, who was a few paces ahead, gazing out at the desolation before them. Her profile was serene, determined. A simple pilgrimage, she’d said.

The silver in his purse felt suddenly like lead. The rust on his sword felt like a sentence. And the freshly carved eye on the gatepost felt like a promise—that the past was not buried in ruins at all. It was awake. It was watching.

And it was waiting for them in the Wastes.